sentence: Chicago, IL - January 18, 2016 - Zacks.com announces the list of stocks featured in the Analyst Blog.
Every day the Zacks Equity Research analysts discuss the latest news and events impacting stocks and the financial markets.
Stocks recently featured in the blog include Coca-Cola Co. ( KO ), Walt Disney Co. ( DIS ), Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ), JPMorgan Chase & Co. ( JPM ) and Intel Corp. ( INTC ).
Today, Zacks is promoting its ''Buy'' stock recommendations.
Get #1Stock of the Day pick for free .

Here are highlights from Friday's Analyst Blog:

The Dow had a relatively better week after the prior week's grievous losses.
The index gained modestly on Monday despite declining crude prices.
The index moved upward again on Tuesday boosted by gains in technology and healthcare stocks.
The Dow declined sharply on Wednesday, dragged lower by declining consumer discretionary and biotech stocks.
However, the index made a strong comeback on Thursday, boosted by a rebound in crude prices.
The Dow has gained marginally during the first four trading days, increasing 0.2%.
Stocks ended mixed on Monday with the index posting modest gains amidst declining oil prices .
Consumer staples garnered the highest gains, with The Coca-Cola Co. ( KO ) ending 0.2% higher.
However, gains were reduced due to losses incurred by energy shares which were adversely affected by declining oil prices.
The Dow gained 0.3% to close about 50 points higher.
But for 9 of the 30 components, all others finished in the green.
Energy shares declined due to a fresh rout in oil prices.
Oil prices plunged to a fresh 12-year low as investors expect China's demand for oil to decline further in 2016.
Exxon Mobil and Chevron declined 1.3% and 1.7%, respectively.
The index increased 0.7% on Tuesday boosted by gains in technology and healthcare stocks.
Price of U.S. crude fell below the $30 a barrel level for a short while for the first time since 2003.
A surging U.S. dollar was the primary reason for the downward slide.
Also, a supply glut, concerns about China's weak economy and volatility in stock markets continue to have negative impacts on oil prices.
WTI Crude declined 3.2% to settle at $30.44 a barrel, its lowest finish since Dec 1, 2003.
However, energy shares still managed to end higher at the close.
Exxon Mobil and Chevron gained 2.1% and 1.7%, respectively.
The index lost 364.81 points or 2.2% on Wednesday, dragged lower by declining consumer discretionary and biotech stocks.
Additionally, the continuing rout in oil prices had a negative impact on energy shares.
The Dow ended the day lower, perilously close to its correction territory which is a drop of 10% or more from its 52-week high.
Consumer stocks bore the brunt of the selling pressure on Wednesday.
The Walt Disney Co. ( DIS ) and The Home Depot, Inc. ( HD ) decreased 2.9% and 4.8%, respectively.
Rise in crude stockpiles along with jump in gasoline and distillate supplies had a negative impact on Brent Crude.
However, U.S. crude price increased for the first time in the last eight trading sessions.
The decline in Brent Crude had an adverse impact on energy shares.
Shares of Chevron lost 1%.
The index gained 1.4% or 227.64 points on Thursday, boosted by a strong rebound in crude prices.
WTI and Brent Crude gained 2.4% each to settle above $31 per barrel.
Energy stocks led the gainers for the day after crude prices rebounded from their lowest levels in 12 years.
Chevron and Exxon Mobil gained 5.1% and 4.6%, respectively.
The dollar moved upward following gains in broader markets.
Additionally, the St. Louis Fed President James Bullard said that achieving the target rate on inflation may take some time.
These events bolstered those investors who were hoping for a slower pace of rate hikes.
Meanwhile, Dow component JPMorgan Chase & Co. ( JPM ) reported encouraging results, leading to optimism about upcoming earnings.
JPMorgan reported fourth quarter earnings per share of $1.32 per share, which beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $1.26.
Earnings increased 10.9% from the year-ago figure of $1.19.
Results were affected by weak trading and asset management.
However, an increase in revenues and fall in expenditures helped earnings to increase on a year-over-year basis.
Managed net revenue for the quarter came in at $23.7 billion, higher than the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $23.1 billion.
This is 1% higher than the figure reported a year earlier.
The increase was primarily a result of higher revenues from Corporate and Consumer and Community Banking.
Non-interest expense declined 7% from the year-ago period to $14.3 billion.
This was a result of a fall in compensation and legal expenses.
Intel Corp. ( INTC ) reported fourth quarter earnings per share of 74 cents, higher than the Zacks Consensus Estimate of 63 cents.
Revenues came in at $14.9 billion, ahead of the Zacks Consensus Estimate of $14.8 billion.
However, shares declined 3% following the release of earnings numbers in after-market trading.
Gross margin declined to 64.3% from 65.4% reported in the year-ago quarter.
Currently, Intel expects a gross margin of 58% for the first quarter of 2016.
This will amount to 62% after excluding certain items.
Intel's enterprise business registered better-than-expected performance.
Sales from PCs came in at $8.8 billion, also exceeding expectations.
However, data center numbers were disappointing.
Revenues from the Data Center business came in at $4.3 billion, lower than the estimated figure of $4.4 billion.
